    <h1>Understanding Password Hashing</h1>
    <p>Password hashing is a crucial component of modern security practices, ensuring that user passwords are stored securely. Hashing transforms a password into a fixed-length string of characters, which is then stored instead of the plain-text password. This process enhances security by making it difficult for attackers to retrieve the original password from the hashed value.</p>
    
    <h2>What is Password Hashing?</h2>
    <p>Hashing is a one-way cryptographic function that converts input data into a fixed-size string of characters. For password hashing, this means that the original password cannot be easily reconstructed from the hash value. Common hashing algorithms used for passwords include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>SHA-256:</strong> Part of the SHA-2 family, it generates a 256-bit hash value.</li>
      <li><strong>Bcrypt:</strong> A key derivation function designed specifically for hashing passwords, incorporating a salt to defend against rainbow table attacks.</li>
      <li><strong>Argon2:</strong> The winner of the Password Hashing Competition, known for its resistance to GPU cracking attacks.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Why Hash Passwords?</h2>
    <p>Storing passwords as plain text is highly insecure, as anyone with access to the database can see the passwords directly. Hashing passwords before storing them provides several benefits:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Enhanced Security:</strong> Hashing ensures that even if an attacker gains access to the database, they cannot easily retrieve the original passwords.</li>
      <li><strong>Salting:</strong> Adding a unique salt to each password before hashing increases the difficulty of precomputed attacks and ensures that identical passwords have different hashes.</li>
      <li><strong>Defensive Against Rainbow Tables:</strong> Rainbow tables are precomputed tables used to reverse cryptographic hash functions. Hashing with salts mitigates the effectiveness of these tables.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2>Best Practices for Password Hashing</h2>
    <p>To ensure robust password security, follow these best practices:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use Strong Hashing Algorithms:</strong> Choose algorithms designed for password hashing, like Bcrypt or Argon2, which are resistant to modern attack techniques.</li>
      <li><strong>Incorporate Salts:</strong> Generate a unique salt for each password to protect against dictionary and rainbow table attacks.</li>
      <li><strong>Regularly Update Hashing Practices:</strong> Stay informed about advancements in hashing techniques and update your practices as necessary to maintain security.</li>
    </ul>
    
    <p>Password hashing is a fundamental aspect of securing user accounts and protecting sensitive information. By understanding and implementing effective hashing techniques, you can significantly enhance the security of your applications.</p>
